title Nock lap 3 -- the edit primitive and opcode 10; the whole core real
prompt kg
think Read my own last recommendation as an actual invitation rather than a closed door: I had named opcode 10 as needing "its own design pass... not a mechanical continuation," and "kg" this session has consistently meant proceed, including through real design work, not only trivial continuation. Chose to do the design pass properly rather than defer it again.
think Designed edit() (#[axis value tree]) as the constructive mirror of slot()'s own already-proven bit-walk, rather than transcribing Hoon's own recursive #[...] definition literally (which reads awkwardly when converted directly). Recorded each level's untouched sibling and which side was chosen on the way down, in a fixed-size array bounded by a u64 axis's own bit-width (at most 64 levels, a true bound, not an arbitrary constant); rebuilt the tree on the way back up, consing each recorded sibling back on in reverse order. This is genuinely iterative, needing no depth counter at all -- a cleaner fit for TAME's own bounded-recursion discipline than eval/eql's explicit counters, since the bound here is provable from the type itself.
think Verified the whole edit() design by hand against a concrete example before writing a line of code: editing axis 6 within [[4 5] [6 [14 15]]] to 999, tracing both the descend pass (recording [4 5] then [14 15] as siblings, with their respective directions) and the ascend pass (rebuilding from 999 outward), landing on [[4 5] [999 [14 15]]] -- confirmed by the actual run afterward, matching the hand trace exactly.
think Implemented opcode 10's two forms by discriminating on whether head(f2) is a cell (the real edit form, *[a 10 [b c] d] = #[b *[a c] *[a d]]) or an atom (the bare-hint form, *[a 10 b c] = *[a c], the same shape opcode 11's own atom form already proved).
think Caught a real regression immediately by rebuilding and rerunning lap 2 before assuming it still held, rather than only running the new lap 3 witness: my own edit to insert the opcode-10 case had accidentally deleted the entire pre-existing opcode-11 case (the StrReplace's old_string included both the 11 case and the trailing else, and my new_string only supplied the new 10 case plus a new else, silently dropping 11). Fixed by re-inserting the opcode-11 handler in its correct position and rebuilding both laps to confirm.
think Applied the lesson from two turns ago proactively this time, before it bit again: lap 1's own witness used opcode 10 to prove "unimplemented" -- about to become false the moment opcode 10 landed. Checked and fixed this BEFORE building, moving the "still unimplemented" test to opcode 12 (genuinely outside Nock's own 0-11 core), rather than discovering the crash after the fact the way opcode 6's own stale fixture did last time.
think Proved opcode 10's edit form against the OFFICIAL reduction rule by independent reconstruction, not merely by matching my own native dispatch to itself: separately evaluated *[a c] and *[a d], fed those results to a direct edit() call, and asserted the result matches the native opcode-10 dispatch exactly -- the same "reduces to its stated rule, proven not argued" discipline lap 2 already established.
think Cross-built lap 3 for riscv64 and confirmed byte-identical output before folding it into tools/glow_riscv_target_witness.rish as the eighth keystone piece, keeping this session's own running practice of proving every new piece on the same substrate as its elders.
obs With this lap, Nock's own numbered core (0 through 11) is now entirely real in this interpreter -- not a partial or illustrative subset, the actual complete primitive-plus-macro spec Urbit's own documentation defines. Worth naming as a real milestone reached across three sequential laps in one continuous thread, each honestly scoped rather than rushed together.
obs The regression this turn (accidentally deleting the opcode-11 case) is the second time in three Nock laps that an existing witness's own fixture became stale the moment a new opcode landed -- a real, repeating pattern worth naming plainly: any witness that tests "X is unimplemented" is load-bearing against a specific, moving fact, and needs to be re-checked at implementation time, not just at authoring time.
file nock/nock_core.rye edit() added (bounded, iterative, two-pass); opcode 10's two-form dispatch added to eval(); a real deleted-case regression (opcode 11) caught and fixed before this landed
file nock/nock_core_witness.rye the "still unimplemented" fixture moved from opcode 10 (now real) to opcode 12 (genuinely outside the spec's core), fixed proactively before building this time
file nock/nock_lap3_witness.rye new -- eight claims: edit() directly at three axes, opcode 10's two forms dispatched end to end, an independent reconstruction of the official rule, and two boundary checks
file tools/nock_lap3_witness.rish new Rishi wrapper, wired into tools/parity_ch01.rish
file tools/glow_riscv_target_witness.rish extended from seven to eight keystone pieces with Nock lap 3, cross-built and confirmed byte-identical
file nock/README.md lap 3 section added; the "opcode 10 unimplemented" reference in the lap-1 row corrected to opcode 12
